{{Infobox amusement park | name = Earth Quest Adventures | image = | caption = | location = [[New Caney, Texas]], U.S. | location2 = | location3 = | coordinates =
| address = | phone_number = | homepage = http://www.earthquestadventures.com/ | owner = Global EarthQuest Holdings (This entity is now bankrupt.) | general_manager = | operator = Contour Entertainment | opening_date = Never opened or built (The date has passed.) | closing_date = | previous_names = | season = | area = | rides = | coasters = | water_rides = | slogan = An Extraordinary Entertainment Resort Destination | footnotes = }}
'''Earth Quest Adventures''' was a planned resort located in [[New Caney, Texas]], approximately {{convert|25|mi|km}} north of [[Houston]].<ref> {{citeweb|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/2012-04-12/news/earthquest-green-amusement-park/full/ |title=Fantasy Land |accessdate= |year = |month= |publisher = Houston Press |work=}}</ref> Contour Entertainment is the resort's master planner and lead designer. The planned {{convert|1600|acre|km2|adj=on}} resort was to include a [[theme park]] as well as a water park, hotel, conference center, retail and office developments.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Contour Entertainment | accessdate = 2009-08-31 | url = http://www.contourentertainment.com/ }}</ref> The size of the theme park was reported to be {{convert|200|acre|km2}} on opening.<ref>{{cite web |title=Earth Quest Adventures drives ahead with plans, drawings |url=http://www.hcnonline.com/articles/2009/02/13/kingwood_observer/news/08realtor.txt |last=Summer |first=Jennifer |date=2009-02-13 |accessdate=2009-08-08 |publisher=Houston Community Newspaper |work=The Kingwood Observer }}</ref> The first phase was planned to begin in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourtribune.com/article.php?id=2813 |title=Dinosaur park promises mega fun |last=Oliver |first=Patsy |date=2008-02-20 |accessdate=2009-08-08 |work=The Tribune |publisher=Ourtribune.com }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/houston/stories/2006/11/13/story11.html |title=Dinosaur theme park may roar into Montgomery County |work=Houston Business Journal |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=2006-11-10 |accessdate=2009-08-08 |first=Greg |last=Barr }}</ref>
The creator and founder of the park, dinosaur expert and author "Dino" Don Lessem, described it as a $500 million project with about 50 rides, including being inside a volcano, an ice cave, as well as coasters, and technologies that hadn’t been used before.<ref>{{Cite web | title = EarthQuest Is No "Dinosaur Park" | work = IAAPA - FUNWORLD Magazine March 2009 | accessdate = 2009-08-31 | url = http://www.iaapa.org/industry/funworld/2009/mar/departments/industrynotes.asp }}</ref> On November 17, 2010, Earth Quest was redesigned to cut the cost from $500 million to $300 million and to add construction phases. These changes were being made to secure and satisfy the project's investors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hcnonline.com/east_montgomery/news/article_77d711fb-5fd9-5f3f-a27a-16d68f507d70.html |title=Money holds up EarthQuest; investors want re-phased project |publisher=Houston Community Newspaper |last=Willert |first=tim |accessdate=2010-11-17 |date=2010-11-15 }}</ref>According to the official Contour Entertainment website, the first phase of the project was to premiere in late 2012 or early 2013. In 2011, the company that owned the land filed for bankruptcy, and "no construction had begun" on the park. <ref>{{Cite web | title = EarthQuest Institute Fraud Continues / Don Allen Holbrook CEO | work = http://www.realscam.com | accessdate = 2018-10-13 | url = http://www.realscam.com/f14/earthquest-institute-fraud-continues-don-allen-holbrook-ceo-2349/ }}</ref>Contour Entertainment has not repurchased the land for the park that was lost in bankruptcy. It was to be repurchased by December 15, 2013, but the date has passed.
